# Public Prosecutor _v_ Lye Boon Sing  

### \[2022\] SGDC 77

<table id="info-table"><tbody><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Case Number</td><td class="txt-body">TP 211007125511-1</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Decision Date</td><td class="txt-body">13 April 2022</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Tribunal/Court</td><td class="txt-body">District Court</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Coram</td><td class="txt-body">Shawn Ho</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Counsel Name(s)</td><td class="txt-body">Sheena Tjoa (Attorney-General's Chambers) for the Prosecution; Accused in Person.</td></tr><tr class="info-row"><td class="txt-label" style="padding: 4px 0px; white-space: nowrap" valign="top">Parties</td><td class="txt-body">Public Prosecutor — Lye Boon Sing</td></tr></tbody></table>

Criminal Law – Statutory Offences – Road Traffic Act

13 April 2022

### District Judge Shawn Ho:

## Introduction

1       The Accused, Mr Lye Boon Sing, is a taxi driver.

2       He claimed trial to one count of driving his taxi without reasonable consideration for other persons using the road and causing hurt to two cyclists, under s 65(1)(b) punishable under s 65(4)(b) of the Road Traffic Act.

3       The Prosecution stated that the Accused did not stop at the stop line. His taxi encroached onto the path of two cyclists who were going straight at the junction from his right. As a result, both cyclists were injured.

4       As against this, the Accused claimed that he had stopped at the stop line for about half a second. He checked but did not see any cyclists coming from his right. His view of the cyclists was obscured by (a) bushes, (b) a sharp bend on the road, (c) the street lighting and (d) the cyclists’ speed.

5       Taken as a whole, the evidence showed that the Accused failed to give way when turning right at the junction, encroaching onto the path of both cyclists. The Prosecution had proven its case beyond a reasonable doubt.

6       I set out my reasons for the conviction.

## Charge

7       The Accused faced one charge:

> You, Lye Boon Sing (Male/ 49 years old, Singaporean) are, charged that you, on 20 April 2021 at or about 9.46 p.m., at the non-signalised junction of West Camp Road and West Camp Road, near lamp post 89, Singapore, did drive a motor vehicle bearing registration number SHA1977A on a road without reasonable consideration for other persons using the road, to wit, by failing to give way while you were turning right at said junction, which failure resulted in you encroaching onto the path of two cyclists, Lee Pang Lim (male / 49 years old) and Tay Beng Hoe Benjamin (male / 23 years old) who were going straight at the junction from your right, and hurt was caused to said two cyclists by such driving, and you have thereby committed an offence under s 65(1)(b) of the Road Traffic Act (Cap 276, 2004 Rev Ed) (“RTA”).

> And further that you, before the commission of the said offence, were convicted on 8 April 1997 for an offence of speeding under s 63(4) read with s 63(1) RTA, which conviction has not been set aside, and you are thereby liable to be punished under s 65(4)(b) of the RTA.[\[note: 1\]](#Ftn_1)

## Prosecution’s case

8       The Accused did not stop at the stop line. His taxi had encroached onto the path of two cyclists who were going straight at the junction from his right. As a result, both cyclists were injured.

## Defence’s case

9       The Accused stopped at the stop line for about half a second. He checked but did not see any cyclists coming from his right. His view of the cyclists was obscured by (a) bushes, (b) a sharp bend on the road, (c) the street lighting and (d) the cyclists’ speed.

## Issues to be determined

10     The issues to be determined were:

> (a)     Did the Accused stop at the stop line (“Issue 1”) and

> (b)     Was the Accused’s view of the cyclists obscured (“Issue 2”)?

11     Briefly, my answer was ‘No’ to both issues.

## Issue 1: Did the Accused stop at the stop line?

12     Section 72 of the Highway Code reads:

> At a junction look right, then left, then right again. **_Do not move off_** **until you are sure that it is safe to do so**”

> \[emphasis added\]

> (see also _Wilkinson’s Road Traffic Offences_, Sweet & Maxwell (28th Ed, 2017, General Editor: Kevin McCormac) at \[6-42\])

13     The Accused said that he stopped at the stop line for about half a second.

14     However, this was not in keeping with the evidence. It was clear from his in-car camera footage — which the Accused called “solid proof” — that the Accused did not stop at the stop line. The Investigation Officer, Station Inspector Ng Beifeng (“IO”),[\[note: 2\]](#Ftn_2) testified that the footage showed that the Accused did not stop at the stop line and he was just moving forward at the uncontrolled T-junction. Based on the evidence, I found that the Accused did not stop at, before, or close to the stop line.

15     I paused here to note that several times during the trial, the Accused stated that he would accept the punishment if he was charged with not stopping at the stop line. He first mentioned this while cross-examining the IO and repeated it during his own evidence-in-chief.

16     For completeness, the photograph[\[note: 3\]](#Ftn_3) taken by the Accused showed his taxi’s position at the material time. His taxi was some distance past the stop line.

![](data:image;base64,)

17     I accepted both cyclists’ evidence. The cyclists and the Accused do not know each other.

18     The first cyclist, Mr Lee Pang Lim (“Mr Lee”),[\[note: 4\]](#Ftn_4) is an experienced cyclist. He had cycled for almost 20 years, 6 days a week before the incident. Mr Lee represented Singapore as a cyclist at the Southeast Asian Games, which is better known as the SEA Games.

19     Mr Lee was cycling in lane 2. As the Accused’s taxi encroached onto his path, he had to swerve his bicycle to avoid colliding with the taxi. Mr Lee somersaulted, fell and became unconscious. Mr Lee’s testimony was consistent with the police report he lodged on 23 April 2021.[\[note: 5\]](#Ftn_5)

20     The second cyclist, Mr Tay Beng Hoe Benjamin (“Mr Tay”),[\[note: 6\]](#Ftn_6) was cycling behind Mr Lee. During the incident, Mr Tay had to swing his bicycle to the right to avoid Mr Lee. Mr Tay fell because his bicycle collided with Mr Lee’s bicycle. Mr Tay’s testimony was consistent with the police report he lodged on 21 April 2021:[^7]

> My friend was cycling at the front and I was behind him when a Comfort Taxi (SHA 1977A) came out of the T-junction trying to make a right turn suddenly. From what I can remember, the taxi was still moving when my friend was swerving to avoid the collision which then caused my friend to fall off his bicycle and I hit onto his bicycle which caused me to fly off from my bicycle.

21     Both cyclists sustained injuries.

22     Mr Lee sustained right facial abrasions, chin laceration, chipped incisor, right hand laceration and fracture of the thyroid cartilage.[\[note: 8\]](#Ftn_8) He was given 18 days of medical leave.[^9] Mr Lee is undergoing therapy for his frozen shoulder and he is nervous about cycling at night.

23     Mr Tay sustained small abrasions over his arms[\[note: 10\]](#Ftn_10) and a 15cm abrasion over his right shin.[^11] He was given 2 days of medical leave.[^12]

## Issue 2: Was the Accused’s view of the cyclists obscured?

### Bushes

24     At its heart, the Accused’s argument was that his view of the cyclists was obscured by overgrown bushes, situated about 25 metres from the stop line. By failing to trim these bushes, the relevant authorities had prioritised Singapore being a “City in a Garden” and “Garden City” over road safety.

25     This argument did not stand.

26     It was not in keeping with the objective evidence such as the in-car camera footage (“footage”)[\[note: 13\]](#Ftn_13) and photograph taken on the day of the incident,[^14] which showed that the bushes were fairly low-lying.

27     Allied to this, Staff Sergeant Nur Alif bin Mohamed Bakri (“SSgt Alif”)[\[note: 15\]](#Ftn_15) testified that the height of the bushes was not really that high. He added that the bushes were all of equivalent height and neatly shaved. SSgt’s view was that a driver would be able to see the cyclists’ head and half of their body. In similar vein, the IO’s testimony was that the bushes were not that high as to obscure the view of the cyclists.

28     Importantly, there is a stretch of road of at least 15 to 25 metres that is fairly straight and unblocked, which afforded the Accused an excellent view of any incoming vehicles if he had stopped at the stop line (which he had failed to do). This found expression in the following photograph:[\[note: 16\]](#Ftn_16)

![](data:image;base64,)

29     Finally, it stands to reason that it would have been easier to spot a group of cyclists, vis-à-vis a solitary cyclist.

### Bend on the road

30     The Accused intimated that there was a sharp bend in the road. SSgt Alif disagreed and testified that it was only a “slight bend”. Given the photographs of the scene, I accepted SSgt Alif’s evidence.

### Street Lighting

31     The Accused stated that the fact that it was quite dark on his taxi’s right side, coupled with both cyclists having worn black jerseys, obscured his view of the cyclists.

32     I was unable to accept the Accused’s contention for the following four interlacing points.

33     First, his claim was not in keeping with the objective evidence such as the footage[\[note: 17\]](#Ftn_17) and photograph taken on the day of the incident,[^18] which showed that the street lighting was good.

34     Second, all the prosecution witnesses[\[note: 19\]](#Ftn_19) testified that the street lighting was good:

> (a)     Mr Lee stated that the street lighting was bright.

> (b)     Mr Tay stated that the street lamps were switched on and the road was brightly lit.

> (c)     SSgt Alif testified that the road was well lit by the lamppost lights.

> (d)     The IO stated that the street lamp was very bright, with clear visibility of the road.

35     Third, there was unchallenged testimony by both cyclists that their bicycles had lights in front, which militated against accepting the Accused’s version.

36     Fourth, Mr Tay was wearing a white (not black) jersey.

37     The First Police Officer’s Accident Report stated that the weather was clear, the road surface was dry and there was no traffic.[\[note: 20\]](#Ftn_20)

### Speed of the cyclists

38     The Accused essayed the following argument: given that the cyclists said that they were travelling at 40kmph (i.e. 11.1 metres per second), in a 5-second period the cyclists would be about 55 metres away, _viz._ they would be cycling along a sharp bend in the road and obscured by the overgrown bushes.

39     I was unable to accept the Accused’s argument for the following reasons. My findings are that the road has a slight bend (at \[30\]) and the bushes were not overgrown (at \[26\]-\[27\]). Simply put, one did not need 5 seconds to look left and then right again. I accepted the Prosecution’s point that in 2 seconds, the cyclists would be about 22 metres away (i.e. 11.1 metres per second, based on 40kmph) and would be clearly visible to the Accused along the stretch of road that is fairly straight and unblocked if he had stopped at the stop line. 40kmph was within the speed limit.

## Verdict

40     Taken as a whole, the Prosecution had proven its case beyond a reasonable doubt against the Accused. He was convicted on the charge.

## Conclusion

41     I am grateful for the hard work of both sides. I will proceed to hear submissions on sentence.
